Self-Driving Car Engineer Nanodegree¶

Deep Learning¶

Project: Build a Traffic Sign Recognition Classifier¶

The goals / steps of this project are the following:

  • Load the data set
  • Explore, summarize and visualize the data set
  • Design, train and test a model architecture
  • Use the model to make predictions on new images
  • Analyze the softmax probabilities of the new images
  • Summarize the results with a written report

Step 0: Load The Data¶

    train = pickle.load(f)

    valid = pickle.load(f)
with open(testing_file, mode='rb') as f:
    test = pickle.load(f)
    
X_train, y_train = train['features'], train['labels']
X_valid, y_valid = valid['features'], valid['labels']
X_test, y_test = test['features'], test['labels']

# Ensure that the features and the labels are the same
# size for each set of data
assert(len(X_train) == len(y_train))
assert(len(X_valid) == len(y_valid))
assert(len(X_test) == len(y_test))

Step 2: Design and Test a Model Architecture¶

Pre-process the Data Set (normalization, grayscale, etc.)¶

The data set is normalized and a grayscale version and HSV version is attached to each image (I changed the depth from 3, RGB, to 7 in this manner). This allows the CNN to have additional points of information to learn from.

In [7]:
import random

def preprocess_data_set(data_set, y_data, extend=False):
    """This function will take the input data sets and prepare them for the
    model by adding a grayscale version and HSV version to the depth of the
    original set. The original data set will have an assumed depth of 3 (RGB)
    and the returned dataset will have a depth of 7.
    
    The function will also extend the data set with translated, rotated and
    zoomed copies of the original dataset if desired.
    
    Parameters
    ==========
    
    data_set: list like
        This is the collection of original images that are being processed.
        It is assumed that these images are rgb
    y_data: list like
        This is the collection of labels associated with the data set
    extend: Boolean
        This will let the function know whether or not to extend the data
        set with translated, rotated and zoomed versions of the images
        
    Returns
    =======
    
    result: array
        This is the array of the processed images
    y_data: list like
        This is the collection of labels associated with the result array
    """
    
    # If the extend flag is True, concatenate translated, rotated and
    # zoomed image sets to the original data set and concatenate the y_data
    # set to itself to compensate
    if extend:
        # Retrieve the shape information of the input data set
        rows, cols, depth = data_set[0].shape

        # Create a translated image set
        translate = []
        movement = [-2, -1, 1, 2]
        for i in data_set:
            x_move = random.choice(movement)
            y_move = random.choice(movement)
            rot_matrix = np.float32([[1, 0, x_move], [0, 1, y_move]])
            translate.append(cv2.warpAffine(i, rot_matrix, (cols, rows)))

        # Create a rotated image set
        rotate = []
        movement = [-15, -10, -5, 5, 10, 15]
        for i in data_set:
            angle = random.choice(movement)
            rot_matrix = cv2.getRotationMatrix2D((cols/2, rows/2), angle, 1)
            rotate.append(cv2.warpAffine(i, rot_matrix, (cols, rows)))

        # Create a scaled image set
        zoom = []
        sizes = [0.9, 1.1]
        for i in data_set:
            zoomfactor = random.choice(sizes)
            rot_matrix = cv2.getRotationMatrix2D((cols/2, rows/2), 0, zoomfactor)
            zoom.append(cv2.warpAffine(i, rot_matrix, (cols, rows)))

        # Concatenate the translated, rotated and scaleded images with the
        # original set
        data_set = np.concatenate((data_set, translate, rotate, zoom))
        y_data = np.concatenate((y_data, y_data, y_data, y_data))
    
    # Create and normalize a grayscale version of the dataset
    gray = []
    for i in data_set:
        gray.append(cv2.cvtColor(i, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY))
        gray[-1] = gray[-1].astype(float)
        for x in gray[-1]:
            for y in range(len(x)):
                x[y] = (x[y] - 128)/128
            

    # Create and normalize an HSV version of the dataset
    hsv = []
    for i in data_set:
        hsv.append(cv2.cvtColor(i, cv2.COLOR_RGB2HSV))
        hsv[-1] = hsv[-1].astype(float)
        for x in hsv[-1]:
            for y in range(len(x)):
                x[y][0] = (x[y][0] - 128)/128
                x[y][1] = (x[y][1] - 128)/128
                x[y][2] = (x[y][2] - 128)/128
        
    # Normalize the original RGB data_set
    norm = []
    for i in data_set:
        norm.append(np.copy(i))
        norm[-1] = norm[-1].astype(float)
        for x in norm[-1]:
            for y in range(len(x)):
                x[y][0] = (x[y][0] - 128)/128
                x[y][1] = (x[y][1] - 128)/128
                x[y][2] = (x[y][2] - 128)/128
    
    # Append the gray and hsv images to the result image
    # set (this will change the depth of the image from 3 to 7)
    result = np.zeros([data_set.shape[0], data_set.shape[1],
                       data_set.shape[2], 7])
    for i in range(len(result)):
        for x in range(len(result[0])):
            for y in range(len(result[0][0])):
                result[i][x][y] = np.append(norm[i][x][y],
                                            [gray[i][x][0], 
                                             hsv[i][x][y][0],
                                             hsv[i][x][y][1],
                                             hsv[i][x][y][2]])

    
    return result, y_data


# Pre-process the training, validation and test sets. Saving and loading used
# to save time when using the processed sets later. The data sets were too
# large for pickle to handle and so numpy is used for the saving and loading operations.
preprocess_images_directory = 'preprocess-traffic-signs-data'
if not os.path.exists(preprocess_images_directory):
    os.makedirs(preprocess_images_directory)
    X_train, y_train = preprocess_data_set(X_train, y_train, extend=True)
    X_valid, y_valid = preprocess_data_set(X_valid, y_valid)
    X_test, y_test = preprocess_data_set(X_test, y_test)
    with open(os.path.join(preprocess_images_directory, 'train.npz'), 'wb') as train_file:

    with open(os.path.join(preprocess_images_directory, 'valid.npz'), 'wb') as valid_file:

else:

        X_valid = data['arr_0']
        y_valid = data['arr_1']
    with open(os.path.join(preprocess_images_directory, 'test.npz'), 'rb') as test_file:
        data = np.load(test_file, allow_pickle=False)
        X_test = data['arr_0']

Model Architecture¶

The architecture that is selected is a modified LeNet CNN. The layer structure is preserved but the size of each layer is altered to improve performance.

In [8]:
import tensorflow as tf
from tensorflow.contrib.layers import flatten

def CovNet(x): 
    """This function defines the convolutional network architecture
    that I used for this project. The overall architecture is that
    of the LeNet implementation with the sizes of the layers altered.
    
    Parameters
    ==========
    
    x: TensorFlow tensor (?, 32, 32, 7)
        This is the input tensor to the convolutional network
        
    Returns
    =======
    
    logits: TensorFlox Tensor (?, 43)
        This is the output of the convolutional network
    """
    
    # Arguments used for tf.truncated_normal, randomly defines variables
    # for the weights and biases for each layer
    mu = 0
    sigma = 0.1
    
    
    # Layer 1: Convolutional. Input = 32x32x7. Output = 28x28x20.
    l1weights = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([5, 5, 7, 20], mu, sigma))
    l1bias = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(20))
    layer1 = tf.nn.conv2d(x, l1weights, [1, 1, 1, 1], 'VALID')
    layer1 = tf.nn.bias_add(layer1, l1bias)

    # Layer 1 Activation Function: RELU
    layer1 = tf.nn.relu(layer1)

    # Layer 1 Pooling: Input = 28x28x20. Output = 14x14x20.
    pool1 = tf.nn.max_pool(layer1, [1, 2, 2, 1], [1, 2, 2, 1], 'VALID')
    
    
    # Layer 2: Convolutional. Input = 14x14x20 Output = 10x10x42.
    l2weights = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([5, 5, 20, 42], mu, sigma))
    l2bias = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(42))
    layer2 = tf.nn.conv2d(pool1, l2weights, [1, 1, 1, 1], 'VALID')
    layer2 = tf.nn.bias_add(layer2, l2bias)
    
    # Layer 2 Activation Function: RELU
    layer2 = tf.nn.relu(layer2)

    # Layer 2 Pooling: Input = 10x10x42. Output = 5x5x42.
    pool2 = tf.nn.max_pool(layer2, [1, 2, 2, 1], [1, 2, 2, 1], 'VALID')


    # Flatten. Input = 5x5x42. Output = 1050.
    flat = flatten(pool2)
    
    # Layer 3: Fully Connected. Input = 1050. Output = 500.
    l3weights = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([1050, 500], mu, sigma))
    l3bias = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(500))
    layer3 = tf.matmul(flat, l3weights) + l3bias
    
    # Layer 3 Activation Function: RELU
    layer3 = tf.nn.relu(layer3)

    
    # Layer 4: Fully Connected. Input = 500. Output = 120.
    l4weights = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([500, 120], mu, sigma))
    l4bias = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(120))
    layer4 = tf.matmul(layer3, l4weights) + l4bias
    
    # Layer 4 Activation Function: RELU
    layer4 = tf.nn.relu(layer4)

    
    # Layer 5: Fully Connected. Input = 120. Output = 43.
    l5weights = tf.Variable(tf.truncated_normal([120, 43], mu, sigma))
    l5bias = tf.Variable(tf.zeros(43))
    logits = tf.matmul(layer4, l5weights) + l5bias
    
    return logits

x = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, (None, 32, 32, 7))

one_hot_y = tf.one_hot(y, 43)

Training Pipeline¶

In [10]:
# Set up variables needed for the training and the convolutional network model
rate = 0.001
logits = CovNet(x)

# Set up the loss function for the training
cross_entropy = tf.nn.softmax_cross_entropy_with_logits_v2(labels=one_hot_y, logits=logits)
loss_operation = tf.reduce_mean(cross_entropy)

# Set up the optimizer for the training
optimizer = tf.train.AdamOptimizer(learning_rate = rate)
training_operation = optimizer.minimize(loss_operation)

Model Evaluation¶

In [11]:
# Set up the model evaluation parameters
EPOCHS = 10
BATCH_SIZE = 50

# Set up tensors to determine the percentage of correct classifications
correct_prediction = tf.equal(tf.argmax(logits, 1), tf.argmax(one_hot_y, 1))
accuracy_operation = tf.reduce_mean(tf.cast(correct_prediction, tf.float32))


def evaluate(X_data, y_data):
    """This function will determine the averaged accuracy of the model for
    input features and labels.
    
    Parameters
    ==========
    
    X_data: TensorFlow tensor (?, 32, 32, 7)
        This is the input features for which the model will attempt to classify
    y_data: TensorFlow tensor(?, 43)
        This is the one-hot tensor of labels associated with the input features
        
    Returns
    =======
    
    Average Accuracy: float
        The function will return the overall average accuracy of the model
    """
    
    num_examples = len(X_data)
    
    # Sum up the accuracy for each example in the feature and label sets
    total_accuracy = 0
    sess = tf.get_default_session()
    for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
        batch_x, batch_y = X_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE], y_data[offset:offset+BATCH_SIZE]
        accuracy = sess.run(accuracy_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y})
        total_accuracy += (accuracy * len(batch_x))
        
    # Return the average accuracy
    return total_accuracy / num_examples

Train the Model¶

In [12]:
from sklearn.utils import shuffle

# Set up the ability to save the model after it is trained
saver = tf.train.Saver()

with tf.Session() as sess:
    sess.run(tf.global_variables_initializer())
    num_examples = len(X_train)
    
    # Run the training operation for the convolutional neural network
    print("Training...")
    print()
    for i in range(EPOCHS):
        # Shuffle the data each epoch to reduce the effect of the order
        # of the examples
        X_train, y_train = shuffle(X_train, y_train)

        # Run the training operation on the training set splitting up
        # according to batch size
        for offset in range(0, num_examples, BATCH_SIZE):
            end = offset + BATCH_SIZE
            batch_x, batch_y = X_train[offset:end], y_train[offset:end]
            sess.run(training_operation, feed_dict={x: batch_x, y: batch_y})
        
        # Determine and print the accuracy of the training set and validation
        # set each epoch
        training_accuracy = evaluate(X_train, y_train)
        validation_accuracy = evaluate(X_valid, y_valid)
        print("EPOCH {} ...".format(i+1))
        print("Training Accuracy = {:.3f}".format(training_accuracy))
        print("Validation Accuracy = {:.3f}".format(validation_accuracy))
        print()
        
    # When the number of epochs has been reached, save the model
    saver.save(sess, './covnet')
    print("Model saved")

Precision and Recall¶

In [13]:
# Set up arrays to tally correct predictions and false positives
correct = np.zeros((43))
false_positive = np.zeros((43))

# Run the model over the validation set and determine the number 
# of correct predictions and false positives for each sign type
with tf.Session() as sess:
    saver.restore(sess, './covnet')
    for i in range(len(X_valid)):
        output = sess.run(logits, feed_dict={x: [X_valid[i]]})
        if np.argmax(output) == y_valid[i]:
            correct[np.argmax(output)] += 1
        else:
            false_positive[np.argmax(output)] += 1

# Set up the parameters that will be needed to calculate and plot
# the precision and recall
labels = np.arange(0, 43)
instances = collections.Counter(y_valid)

# Calculate the precision and recall
precision = [correct[i]/(correct[i]+false_positive[i]) for i in range(43)]
recall = [correct[i]/instances[i] for i in range(43)]

# Plot the precision and recall that was calculated for each sign type
plt.figure(figsize=[14, 10])
plt.bar(labels, precision)
plt.xlabel('Sign ID')
plt.ylabel('Precision (%)')
plt.title('Calculated Precision For Each Sign Type')
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=[14, 10])
plt.bar(labels, recall)
plt.xlabel('Sign ID')
plt.ylabel('Recall (%)')
plt.title('Calculated Recall For Each Sign Type')
plt.show()
